## Overview
Ryan Smith is the co‑founder and former CEO of Qualtrics, a software company that pioneered the experience management (XM) category. Under his leadership, Qualtrics grew from a college‑spurred startup into a public company valued at over $15 billion at its 2021 IPO, before being acquired by SAP for $8 billion in 2018 (and later re‑spun off). Smith is also a co‑owner of the NBA’s Utah Jazz, having led a purchase group that acquired the team in 2020.

Smith’s impact extends beyond business: he has become a prominent advocate for Utah’s tech ecosystem, investing in local startups and pushing for policies that attract talent and capital to the state. His entrepreneurial story—starting Qualtrics out of his parents’ basement in Provo—serves as a founding narrative for Utah’s “Silicon Slopes” identity.

## Utah connection
Ryan Smith is a Utah native and built Qualtrics in Provo, Utah, at a time when the state was not widely recognized as a tech hub. The company’s success (eventually employing thousands in the region) helped catalyze the growth of Utah’s technology sector, drawing venture capital and talent to the Wasatch Front. Smith remains deeply involved in the local community, serving on boards and supporting initiatives that strengthen Utah’s entrepreneurial infrastructure.

